ttp://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/AEFFA32D-9DEA-4601-A7BC-4048D08F05A5"><gtr:id>AEFFA32D-9DEA-4601-A7BC-4048D08F05A5</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Stacey</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Gutkowski</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH046879%2F1"><gtr:id>6ACCE2AE-309E-4781-A400-E6E9DF6237B9</gtr:id><gtr:title>Secularism, Islam and British security politics, 2001-2010</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H046879/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Since September 11th the experience of secularisation within the modern West has had global repurcussions. Western secularisation has provided a rallying point for radical Islamists keen to destroy what they see as moral corruption in the West and throughout the Muslim world. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The experience of secularisation has also made it difficult for many Westerners to understand why radical Islamism has claimed so many followers, some willing to make the ultimate sacrafice in pursuit of political aims. Using the United Kingdom's experiences (particularly in Iraq and at home) as an in-depth case study, this project explores how that the experience of secularisation in the late modern West has both confused policymakers charged with waging &amp;quot;wars on terror&amp;quot; and enabled some suprising moments of clarity. Comparing the British case to other Western countries, it asks what factors have made the difference between successful engagement and authoritarian mistakes.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>70125</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>My findings are currently being used to re-formulate British Army and MoD policies towards religion and conflict. I have also recently spoken at Chatham House on my findings to the FCO, the State Department, and members of the NGO community.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2014</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>6D864FCC-78AA-4DC2-97A2-0E3C0F722787</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>546de325a8f350.30353748</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Security and Diplomacy</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>On my research on British security policy after 9/11, I found that policy was framed in subtle but important ways by the UK's secular, liberal political tradition, combined with its social milieu of multiculturalism, Christian heritage and widespread indifference to religion. This secular social habitus contributed both to a series of policy mis-steps in Iraq, Afghanistan and at home and also a set of sound policies, such as the inclusion of Islamist parties and groups in the democratic process. The contours of these dynamics are, however, not confined to the UK and have important implications for global politics and public policy.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>I have been involved in the ongoing development of new British army and MoD strategies on religion. In 2014 I was invited lecture to over 200 Army officers up to the rank of 3 star general at the Army Lessons Exploitation Centre on the arguments of my sole-authored book, Secular War: Myths of Religion, Politics and Violence. This lecture was recorded and distributed widely across the British military, security services and government departments. The Lessons Exploitation Centre at the Directorate of Land Warfare has invited me to input into a publication they are developing from the 'lessons learned' working day. In 2013 I advised the Ministry of Defence Concepts and Doctrines Centre on the likely role of religion in British security concerns through to 2045. In 2014, based on this expertise, I was also invited to the Chief of the Defence Staff's forum and to sit on the editorial board of a new journal published by the MoD, the New Strategist. This boasts a small, esteemed board which includes Professors Theo Farrell and Joe Maiolo from King's. In 2012 I contributed expertise on jihad and Islamist politics to the Ministry of Defence Strategic Defence Review, which will shape British security policy for the next two decades.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>36141BB4-AB28-44A6-81AD-B4FB2FDA4D3C</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>546de2ac5a93e8.94157351</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Government, Democracy and Justice,Security and Diplomacy</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aRbb3-0SfwA</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>41FE5438-B2E5-4AEE-89AF-1661201FCB2E</gtr:id><gtr:title>The British Secular
 
